# Noun Genders — Memory Drill

## Purpose

Drill English noun → Greek article + noun as a unit. Gender is not reliably derivable from form; it must be memorised per noun. Without gender automatic, article selection (τον/την/το) requires a conscious intermediate step that breaks production speed.

Prompt: English word → type Greek article + noun (e.g. "house → το σπίτι")

## Why this is distinct from the articles drill

The articles paradigm drill teaches the FORMS of ο/η/το across cases. This drill teaches WHICH article applies to which noun. They are different skills. You need both: the form AND the assignment.

## Core noun set

### Masculine (ο)
| English | Greek (nom sg) |
|---------|----------------|
| man | ο άντρας |
| friend (m) | ο φίλος |
| coffee | ο καφές |
| road / street | ο δρόμος |
| time / weather | ο καιρός |
| father | ο πατέρας |
| son | ο γιος |
| dog | ο σκύλος |
| month | ο μήνας |
| world | ο κόσμος |
| bread | ο άρτος / το ψωμί (neut — use as contrast item) |

### Feminine (η)
| English | Greek (nom sg) |
|---------|----------------|
| woman | η γυναίκα |
| friend (f) | η φίλη |
| sea | η θάλασσα |
| door | η πόρτα |
| city | η πόλη |
| mother | η μητέρα |
| daughter | η κόρη |
| language | η γλώσσα |
| night | η νύχτα |
| family | η οικογένεια |

### Neuter (το)
| English | Greek (nom sg) |
|---------|----------------|
| house | το σπίτι |
| child | το παιδί |
| book | το βιβλίο |
| car | το αυτοκίνητο |
| water | το νερό |
| name | το όνομα |
| food | το φαγητό |
| restaurant | το εστιατόριο |
| hotel | το ξενοδοχείο |
| morning | το πρωί |

## Drill format

**Forward**: English → type `article + noun` (e.g. "house" → "το σπίτι")
**Gender selector**: Allow filtering by gender (drill only feminine, or only masculine vs neuter, etc.) — useful for targeted practice
**Reverse**: Greek noun (no article) → type correct article, or select M/F/N

## Notes

- Accept both nominative article and noun (ο φίλος) in forward mode
- Do NOT drill genitive or accusative forms here — that is the case-transform grammar drill
- Neuter nouns in -ι and -ο are the most learnable as a pattern, but still worth drilling explicitly for the common set
- Masculine -ος endings are common but not universal — don't let learner over-generalise
- Include a few "traps": nouns that look like they should be one gender but aren't (ο καφές looks like it should be neuter but is masculine)
